# TLDR;

Yes, Strings that are not used (used meaning, referenced by another object) will be removed, like any other out-of-scope object.

# Longer Version

*But how do we know for sure?* 

Usually, let&#39;s see what the Java Specification says; my brief search found nothing. 

Next, let&#39;s dive into the standard Java implementation, but the String class also did not help, as the clean-up of Strings is managed within the JVM&#39;s implementation. 

So, finally - if you are curious about how the String Pool marks objects as out of scope, here is the [JDK 8 implementation.][1] 

```
void StringTable::unlink_or_oops_do(BoolObjectClosure* is_alive, OopClosure* f) {
  // Readers of the table are unlocked, so we should only be removing
  // entries at a safepoint.
  assert(SafepointSynchronize::is_at_safepoint(), &quot;must be at safepoint&quot;);
  for (int i = 0; i &lt; the_table()-&gt;table_size(); ++i) {
    HashtableEntry&lt;oop, mtSymbol&gt;** p = the_table()-&gt;bucket_addr(i);
    HashtableEntry&lt;oop, mtSymbol&gt;* entry = the_table()-&gt;bucket(i);
    while (entry != NULL) {
      assert(!entry-&gt;is_shared(), &quot;CDS not used for the StringTable&quot;);

      if (is_alive-&gt;do_object_b(entry-&gt;literal())) {
        if (f != NULL) {
          f-&gt;do_oop((oop*)entry-&gt;literal_addr());
        }
        p = entry-&gt;next_addr();
      } else {
        *p = entry-&gt;next();
        the_table()-&gt;free_entry(entry);
      }
      entry = *p;
    }
  }
}
```
Disclaimer: I am no C++ Developer, but from what I understand is, the code runs through all the String objects and checks if there is a back reference to the String object, if not it frees up the String (entry).


**Random thing:** The Code refers to a StringTable and not the String Pool :) So now you can correct all your friends ;)

  [1]: https://hg.openjdk.org/jdk8/jdk8/hotspot/file/87ee5ee27509/src/share/vm/classfile/symbolTable.cpp#l742

