If the test class is annotated with the below annotations, it would work (JUnit 4)

```
@RunWith(SpringRunner.class)
@SpringBootTest
```

In case of JUnit 5, just annotating with `@SpringBootTest` should be sufficient. Refer [here][1]

&gt; If you are using JUnit 5, there is no need to add the equivalent @ExtendWith(SpringExtension.class) as @SpringBootTest and the other @…​Test annotations are already annotated with it.

Note that this loads the entire Spring Application context which is more suitable for integration testing.

From **unit testing** standpoint, it is recommended to use `@RunWith(MockitoJUnitRunner.class)` with `@InjectMocks` and `@Mock` combination (JUnit 4)

```
@RunWith(MockitoJUnitRunner.class)
class CustomerServiceTest{
   @Mock
   private EmployeeService employeeService;

   @InjectMocks
   private CustomerService customerService;

   @Test
   public void testcustomerIdNotNull() {
